[src:nurbs-surfaces/b-spline] A B-spline is defined as a piecewise polynomial of order n , meaning a degree of $n-1$ .
[src:nurbs-surfaces/b-spline] It is built from sections that meet at these knots, where the continuity of the function and its derivatives depends on how often each knot repeats (its multiplicity).
[src:nurbs-surfaces/b-spline] Any spline function of a specific degree can be uniquely expressed as a linear combination of B-splines of that degree over the same knots, a property that makes them versatile in mathematical modeling.
[src:nurbs-surfaces/b-spline] A special subtype, cardinal B-splines, uses equidistant knots.
[src:nurbs-surfaces/b-spline] The concept of B-splines traces back to the 19th century, when Nikolai Lobachevsky explored similar ideas at Kazan University in Russia, though the term "B-spline" was coined by Isaac Jacob Schoenberg in 1967, reflecting their role as basis functions.
[src:nurbs-surfaces/b-spline] B-splines are widely used in fields like computer-aided design (CAD) and computer graphics, where they shape curves and surfaces through a set of control points, as well as in data analysis for tasks like curve fitting and numerical differentiation of experimental data.
[src:nurbs-surfaces/b-spline] A B-spline of order $p+1$ is a collection of piecewise polynomial functions $B_{i,p}(t)$ of degree p in a variable t .
[src:nurbs-surfaces/b-spline] The values of t where the pieces of polynomial meet are known as knots, denoted $t_{0},t_{1},t_{2},\ldots ,t_{m}$ and sorted into nondecreasing order.
[src:nurbs-surfaces/b-spline] for all t between the knots $t_{p}$ and $t_{m-p}$ , then the scaling factor of $B_{i,p}(t)$ becomes fixed.
[src:nurbs-surfaces/b-spline] The knots in-between (and not including) $t_{p}$ and $t_{m-p}$ are called the internal knots.
[src:nurbs-surfaces/b-spline] B-splines can be constructed by means of the Cox–de Boor recursion formula.
[src:nurbs-surfaces/b-spline] We start with the B-splines of degree $p=0$ , i.e. piecewise constant polynomials.
[src:nurbs-surfaces/b-spline] A B-spline function is a combination of flexible bands that is controlled by a number of points that are called control points, creating smooth curves.
[src:nurbs-surfaces/b-spline] These functions are used to create and manage complex shapes and surfaces using a number of points.
[src:nurbs-surfaces/b-spline] B-spline function and Bézier functions are applied extensively in shape optimization methods.
[src:nurbs-surfaces/b-spline] A B-spline of order n is a piecewise polynomial function of degree $n-1$ in a variable x .
[src:nurbs-surfaces/b-spline] It is defined over n locations $t_{i}$ , called knots or breakpoints, which must be in non-descending order $t_{i}\leq t_{i+1}$ .
[src:nurbs-surfaces/b-spline] The B-spline contributes only in the range between the first and last of these knots and is zero elsewhere.
[src:nurbs-surfaces/b-spline] If each knot is separated by the same distance h (where $h=t_{i+1}-t_{i}$ ) from its predecessor, the knot vector and the corresponding B-splines are called "uniform" (see cardinal B-spline below).
[src:nurbs-surfaces/b-spline] For each finite knot interval where it is non-zero, a B-spline is a polynomial of degree $n-1$ .
[src:nurbs-surfaces/b-spline] A B-spline is a continuous function at the knots.
[src:nurbs-surfaces/b-spline] When all knots belonging to the B-spline are distinct, its derivatives are also continuous up to the derivative of degree $n-2$ .
[src:nurbs-surfaces/b-spline] If the knots are coincident at a given value of x , the continuity of derivative order is reduced by 1 for each additional coincident knot.
[src:nurbs-surfaces/b-spline] B-splines may share a subset of their knots, but two B-splines defined over exactly the same knots are identical.
[src:nurbs-surfaces/b-spline] In other words, a B-spline is uniquely defined by its knots.
[src:nurbs-surfaces/b-spline] One distinguishes internal knots and end points.
[src:nurbs-surfaces/b-spline] Internal knots cover the x -domain one is interested in.
[src:nurbs-surfaces/b-spline] Since a single B-spline already extends over n knots, it follows that the internal knots need to be extended with $n-1$ endpoints on each side, to give full support to the first and last B-spline, which affect the internal knot intervals.
[src:nurbs-surfaces/b-spline] The values of the endpoints do not matter, usually the first or last internal knot is just repeated.
[src:nurbs-surfaces/b-spline] B-splines play the role of basis functions for the spline function space, hence the name.
[src:nurbs-surfaces/b-spline] This property follows from the fact that all pieces have the same continuity properties, within their individual range of support, at the knots.
[src:nurbs-surfaces/b-spline] That is, $B_{i,0}(x)$ is piecewise constant one or zero indicating which knot span *x* is in (zero if knot span *i* is repeated).
[src:nurbs-surfaces/b-spline] ramps from one to zero as *x* goes from $t_{i+1}$ to $t_{i+k+1}$ .
[src:nurbs-surfaces/b-spline] The corresponding *B*s are zero outside those respective ranges.
[src:nurbs-surfaces/b-spline] For example, $B_{i,1}(x)$ is a triangular function that is zero below $x=t_{i}$ , ramps to one at $x=t_{i+1}$ and back to zero at and beyond $x=t_{i+2}$ .
[src:nurbs-surfaces/b-spline] However, because B-spline basis functions have local support, B-splines are typically computed by algorithms that do not need to evaluate basis functions where they are zero, such as de Boor's algorithm.
[src:nurbs-surfaces/b-spline] This relation leads directly to the FORTRAN-coded algorithm BSPLV, which generates values of the B-splines of order *n* at *x*.
[src:nurbs-surfaces/b-spline] The following scheme illustrates how each piece of order *n* is a linear combination of the pieces of B-splines of order *n* − 1 to its left.
[src:nurbs-surfaces/b-spline] Faster variants of the de Boor algorithm have been proposed, but they suffer from comparatively lower stability.
[src:nurbs-surfaces/b-spline] A cardinal B-spline has a constant separation *h* between knots.
[src:nurbs-surfaces/b-spline] The cardinal B-splines for a given order *n* are just shifted copies of each other.
[src:nurbs-surfaces/b-spline] They can be obtained from the simpler definition.
[src:nurbs-surfaces/b-spline] The "placeholder" notation is used to indicate that the *n*-th divided difference of the function $(t-x)_{+}^{n-1}$ of the two variables *t* and *x* is to be taken by fixing *x* and considering $(t-x)_{+}^{n-1}$ as a function of *t* alone.
[src:nurbs-surfaces/b-spline] A cardinal B-spline has uniformly spaced knots, therefore interpolation between the knots equals convolution with a smoothing kernel.
[src:nurbs-surfaces/b-spline] Convolution of the signal $\mathbf {x}$ with a rectangle function $\mathbf {h} =[1/3,1/3,1/3]$ gives first order interpolated B-spline values.
[src:nurbs-surfaces/b-spline] Second-order B-spline interpolation is convolution with a rectangle function twice $\mathbf {y} =\mathbf {x} *\mathbf {h} *\mathbf {h}$ ; by iterative filtering with a rectangle function, higher-order interpolation is obtained.
[src:nurbs-surfaces/b-spline] Fast B-spline interpolation on a uniform sample domain can be done by iterative mean-filtering.
[src:nurbs-surfaces/b-spline] Alternatively, a rectangle function equals sinc in Fourier domain.
[src:nurbs-surfaces/b-spline] Therefore, cubic spline interpolation equals multiplying the signal in Fourier domain with sinc4.
[src:nurbs-surfaces/b-spline] See Irwin–Hall distribution#Special cases for algebraic expressions for the cardinal B-splines of degree 1–4.
[src:nurbs-surfaces/b-spline] The term P-spline stands for "penalized B-spline".
[src:nurbs-surfaces/b-spline] It refers to using the B-spline representation where the coefficients are determined partly by the data to be fitted, and partly by an additional penalty function that aims to impose smoothness to avoid overfitting.
[src:nurbs-surfaces/b-spline] Two- and multidimensional P-spline approximations of data can use the face-splitting product of matrices to the minimization of calculation operations.
[src:nurbs-surfaces/b-spline] which shows that there is a simple relationship between the derivative of a spline function and the B-splines of degree one less.
[src:nurbs-surfaces/b-spline] B-splines where the knot positions lie in a single dimension, can be used to represent 1-d probability density functions $p(x)$ .
[src:nurbs-surfaces/b-spline] and with normalization constant constraint $\sum _{i}c_{i}=1$ .
[src:nurbs-surfaces/b-spline] Here, $\mathbf {t}$ represents a vector with the j knot positions and $\mathbf {m}$ a vector with the respective knot multiplicities.
[src:nurbs-surfaces/b-spline] One can therefore calculate any moment of a probability density function $p(x)$ represented by a sum of B-spline basis functions exactly, without resorting to numerical techniques.
[src:nurbs-surfaces/b-spline] This means that a Bézier curve of degree n given by $m\gg n$ control points consists of about $m/n$ mostly independent segments, whereas the B-spline with the same parameters smoothly transitions from subinterval to subinterval.
[src:nurbs-surfaces/b-spline] To get something comparable from a Bézier curve, one would need to impose a smoothness condition on transitions between segments, resulting in some manner of Bézier spline (for which many control points would be determined by the smoothness requirement).
[src:nurbs-surfaces/b-spline] A piecewise/composite Bézier curve is a series of Bézier curves joined with at least $C^{0}$ continuity (the last point of one curve coincides with the starting point of the next curve).
[src:nurbs-surfaces/b-spline] Depending on the application, additional smoothness requirements (such as $C^{1}$ or $C^{2}$ continuity) may be added. $C^{1}$ continuous curves have identical tangents at the breakpoint (where the two curves meet). $C^{2}$ continuous curves have identical curvature at the breakpoint.
[src:nurbs-surfaces/b-spline] Usually in curve fitting, a set of data points is fitted with a curve defined by some mathematical function.
[src:nurbs-surfaces/b-spline] For example, common types of curve fitting use a polynomial or a set of exponential functions.
[src:nurbs-surfaces/b-spline] When there is no theoretical basis for choosing a fitting function, the curve may be fitted with a spline function composed of a sum of B-splines, using the method of least squares.
[src:nurbs-surfaces/b-spline] where *W*(*x*) is a weight, and *y*(*x*) is the datum value at *x*.
[src:nurbs-surfaces/b-spline] The coefficients $\alpha _{i}$ are the parameters to be determined.
[src:nurbs-surfaces/b-spline] The knot values may be fixed or treated as parameters.
[src:nurbs-surfaces/b-spline] The main difficulty in applying this process is in determining the number of knots to use and where they should be placed. de Boor suggests various strategies to address this problem.
[src:nurbs-surfaces/b-spline] For instance, the spacing between knots is decreased in proportion to the curvature (2nd derivative) of the data.
[src:nurbs-surfaces/b-spline] For instance, the use of B-splines for fitting single Lorentzian and Gaussian curves has been investigated.
[src:nurbs-surfaces/b-spline] Optimal spline functions of degrees 3–7 inclusive, based on symmetric arrangements of 5, 6, and 7 knots, have been computed and the method was applied for smoothing and differentiation of spectroscopic curves.
[src:nurbs-surfaces/b-spline] In a comparable study, the two-dimensional version of the Savitzky–Golay filtering and the spline method produced better results than moving average or Chebyshev filtering.
[src:nurbs-surfaces/b-spline] In computer-aided design and computer graphics applications, a spline curve is sometimes represented as $C(t)$ , a parametric curve of some real parameter t .
[src:nurbs-surfaces/b-spline] In this case the curve $C(t)$ can be treated as two or three separate coordinate functions $(x(t),y(t))$ , or $(x(t),y(t),z(t))$ .
[src:nurbs-surfaces/b-spline] The coordinate functions $x(t)$ , $y(t)$ and $z(t)$ are each spline functions, with a common set of knot values $t_{1},t_{2},\ldots ,t_{n}$ .
[src:nurbs-surfaces/b-spline] These points $P_{i}$ are commonly known as control points.
[src:nurbs-surfaces/b-spline] Working in reverse, a sequence of control points, knot values, and order of the B-spline define a parametric curve.
[src:nurbs-surfaces/b-spline] Because the B-splines are non-zero for just a finite number of knot intervals, if a single control point is moved, the corresponding change to the parametric curve is just over the parameter range of a small number knot intervals.
[src:nurbs-surfaces/b-spline] Because $\sum _{i}B_{i,n}(x)=1$ , and at all times each $B_{i,n}(x)\geq 0$ , then the curve remains inside the bounding box of the control points.
[src:nurbs-surfaces/b-spline] Also, in some sense, the curve broadly follows the control points.
[src:nurbs-surfaces/b-spline] A less desirable feature is that the parametric curve does not interpolate the control points.
[src:nurbs-surfaces/b-spline] Usually the curve does not pass through the control points.
[src:nurbs-surfaces/b-spline] A cubic B-spline curve $\mathbf {C} (t)$ with a normalized parameter $t\in [0,1]$ is defined by four nodes (i.e.
[src:nurbs-surfaces/b-spline] A piecewise cubic B-spline is formed by a set of nodes and each four consecutive nodes define a cubic piece of the curve with the formulation above.
[src:nurbs-surfaces/b-spline] If the first and last $n+1$ knots ( n is the degree) of the knot vector have the same value, start and end points of the curve overlap the control points, resulting clamped B-splines.
[src:nurbs-surfaces/b-spline] A clamped B-spline can be divided into piecewise B-spline segments with a normalized parameter $t\in [0,1]$ , defined by four control points ${\textbf {b}}_{i}$ , ${\textbf {b}}_{i+1}$ , ${\textbf {b}}_{i+2}$ , and ${\textbf {b}}_{i+3}$ .
[src:nurbs-surfaces/b-spline] where $\mathbf {R} _{i}$ is a coefficient matrix.
[src:nurbs-surfaces/b-spline] In computer-aided design, computer-aided manufacturing, and computer graphics, a powerful extension of B-splines is non-uniform rational B-splines (NURBS).
[src:nurbs-surfaces/b-spline] NURBS are essentially B-splines in homogeneous coordinates.
[src:nurbs-surfaces/b-spline] Like B-splines, they are defined by their order, and a knot vector, and a set of control points, but unlike simple B-splines, the control points each have a weight.
[src:nurbs-surfaces/b-spline] When the weight is equal to 1, a NURBS is simply a B-spline and as such NURBS generalizes both B-splines and Bézier curves and surfaces, the primary difference being the weighting of the control points which makes NURBS curves "rational".
[src:nurbs-surfaces/b-spline] By evaluating a NURBS at various values of the parameters, the curve can be traced through space; likewise, by evaluating a NURBS surface at various values of the two parameters, the surface can be represented in Cartesian space.
[src:nurbs-surfaces/b-spline] Like B-splines, NURBS control points determine the shape of the curve.
[src:nurbs-surfaces/b-spline] Each point of the curve is computed by taking a weighted sum of a number of control points.
[src:nurbs-surfaces/b-spline] The weight of each point varies according to the governing parameter.
[src:nurbs-surfaces/b-spline] For a curve of degree *d*, the influence of any control point is only nonzero in *d*+1 intervals (knot spans) of the parameter space.
[src:nurbs-surfaces/b-spline] Within those intervals, the weight changes according to a polynomial function (basis functions) of degree *d*.
[src:nurbs-surfaces/b-spline] At the boundaries of the intervals, the basis functions go smoothly to zero, the smoothness being determined by the degree of the polynomial.
[src:nurbs-surfaces/b-spline] The knot vector is a sequence of parameter values that determines where and how the control points affect the NURBS curve.
[src:nurbs-surfaces/b-spline] The number of knots is always equal to the number of control points plus curve degree plus one.
[src:nurbs-surfaces/b-spline] Each time the parameter value enters a new knot span, a new control point becomes active, while an old control point is discarded.
[src:nurbs-surfaces/b-spline] *u* is the independent variable (instead of *x*), *k* is the number of control points, *N* is a B-spline (used instead of *B*), *n* is the polynomial degree, *P* is a control point and *w* is a weight.
[src:nurbs-surfaces/b-spline] The denominator is a normalizing factor that evaluates to one if all weights are one.
[src:nurbs-surfaces/b-spline] are known as the rational basis functions.
[src:nurbs-surfaces/bézier-curve] A **Bézier curve** (/ˈbɛz.i.eɪ/ *BEH-zee-ay*, French pronunciation: [bezje]) is a parametric curve used in computer graphics and related fields.
[src:nurbs-surfaces/bézier-curve] A sequence of discrete "control points" defines a smooth, continuous curve by means of a formula.
[src:nurbs-surfaces/bézier-curve] Usually the curve is intended to approximate a real-world shape that otherwise has no mathematical representation or whose representation is unknown or too complicated.
[src:nurbs-surfaces/bézier-curve] The Bézier curve is named after French engineer Pierre Bézier (1910–1999), who used it in the 1960s for designing curves for the bodywork of Renault cars.
[src:nurbs-surfaces/bézier-curve] Other uses include the design of computer fonts and animation.
[src:nurbs-surfaces/bézier-curve] Bézier curves can be combined to form a Bézier spline, or generalized to higher dimensions to form Bézier surfaces.
[src:nurbs-surfaces/bézier-curve] The Bézier triangle is a special case of the latter.
[src:nurbs-surfaces/bézier-curve] In vector graphics, Bézier curves are used to model smooth curves that can be scaled indefinitely.
[src:nurbs-surfaces/bézier-curve] "Paths", as they are commonly referred to in image manipulation programs, are combinations of linked Bézier curves.
[src:nurbs-surfaces/bézier-curve] Paths are not bound by the limits of rasterized images and are intuitive to modify.
[src:nurbs-surfaces/bézier-curve] Bézier curves are also used in the time domain, particularly in animation, user interface design and smoothing cursor trajectory in eye gaze-controlled interfaces.
[src:nurbs-surfaces/bézier-curve] For example, a Bézier curve can be used to specify the velocity over time of an object such as an icon moving from A to B, rather than simply moving at a fixed number of pixels per step.
[src:nurbs-surfaces/bézier-curve] When animators or interface designers talk about the "physics" or "feel" of an operation, they may be referring to the particular Bézier curve used to control the velocity over time of the move in question.
[src:nurbs-surfaces/bézier-curve] This also applies to robotics where the motion of a welding arm, for example, should be smooth to avoid unnecessary wear.
[src:nurbs-surfaces/bézier-curve] De Casteljau's method was patented in France but not published until the 1980s while the Bézier polynomials were widely publicised in the 1960s by the French engineer Pierre Bézier, who discovered them independently and used them to design automobile bodies at Renault.
[src:nurbs-surfaces/bézier-curve] A Bézier curve is defined by a sequence of *control points* **P**0 through **P***n*, where *n* is called the order of the curve (*n* = 1 for linear, 2 for quadratic, 3 for cubic, etc.).
[src:nurbs-surfaces/bézier-curve] The first and last control points are always the endpoints of the curve; however, the intermediate control points generally do not lie on the curve.
[src:nurbs-surfaces/bézier-curve] The sums in the following sections are to be understood as affine combinations – that is, the coefficients sum to 1.
[src:nurbs-surfaces/bézier-curve] Given distinct points **P**0 and **P**1, a linear Bézier curve is simply a line between those two points.
[src:nurbs-surfaces/bézier-curve] This is the simplest and is equivalent to linear interpolation.
[src:nurbs-surfaces/bézier-curve] The quantity $\mathbf {P} _{1}-\mathbf {P} _{0}$ represents the displacement vector from the start point to the end point.
[src:nurbs-surfaces/bézier-curve] which can be interpreted as the linear interpolant of corresponding points on the linear Bézier curves from **P**0 to **P**1 and from **P**1 to **P**2 respectively.
[src:nurbs-surfaces/bézier-curve] from which it can be concluded that the tangents to the curve at **P**0 and **P**2 intersect at **P**1.
[src:nurbs-surfaces/bézier-curve] As *t* increases from 0 to 1, the curve departs from **P**0 in the direction of **P**1, then bends to arrive at **P**2 from the direction of **P**1.
[src:nurbs-surfaces/bézier-curve] Four points **P**0, **P**1, **P**2 and **P**3 in the plane or in higher-dimensional space define a cubic Bézier curve.
[src:nurbs-surfaces/bézier-curve] The curve starts at **P**0 going toward **P**1 and arrives at **P**3 coming from the direction of **P**2.
[src:nurbs-surfaces/bézier-curve] Usually, it will not pass through **P**1 or **P**2; these points are only there to provide directional information.
[src:nurbs-surfaces/bézier-curve] The distance between **P**1 and **P**2 determines "how far" and "how fast" the curve moves towards **P**1 before turning towards **P**2.
[src:nurbs-surfaces/bézier-curve] For some choices of **P**1 and **P**2 the curve may intersect itself or contain a cusp.
[src:nurbs-surfaces/bézier-curve] Any series of 4 distinct points can be converted to a cubic Bézier curve that goes through all 4 points in order.
[src:nurbs-surfaces/bézier-curve] Given the starting and ending point of some cubic Bézier curve, and the points along the curve corresponding to *t* = 1/3 and *t* = 2/3, the control points for the original Bézier curve can be recovered.
[src:nurbs-surfaces/bézier-curve] For control points whose consecutive triples form two similar triangles with the same orientation, the resulting cubic Bézier curve is an arc of a (scaled and translated) Tschirnhausen cubic.
[src:nurbs-surfaces/bézier-curve] These are Pythagorean hodograph curves, curves whose arc length and offset curves have a rational parameterization, and they are the only cubic curves with these properties.
[src:nurbs-surfaces/bézier-curve] Bézier curves can be defined for any degree *n*.
[src:nurbs-surfaces/bézier-curve] A recursive definition for the Bézier curve of degree *n* expresses it as a point-to-point linear combination (linear interpolation) of a pair of corresponding points in two Bézier curves of degree *n* − 1.
[src:nurbs-surfaces/bézier-curve] This recursion is elucidated in the animations below.
[src:nurbs-surfaces/bézier-curve] where $\scriptstyle {n \choose i}$ are the binomial coefficients.
[src:nurbs-surfaces/bézier-curve] Some terminology is associated with these parametric curves.
[src:nurbs-surfaces/bézier-curve] are known as Bernstein basis polynomials of degree *n*.
[src:nurbs-surfaces/bézier-curve] The points **P***i* are called *control points* for the Bézier curve.
[src:nurbs-surfaces/bézier-curve] The polygon formed by connecting the Bézier points with lines, starting with **P**0 and finishing with **P***n*, is called the *Bézier polygon* (or *control polygon*).
[src:nurbs-surfaces/bézier-curve] The convex hull of the Bézier polygon contains the Bézier curve.
[src:nurbs-surfaces/bézier-curve] Sometimes it is desirable to express the Bézier curve as a polynomial instead of a sum of less straightforward Bernstein polynomials.
[src:nurbs-surfaces/bézier-curve] This could be practical if $\mathbf {C} _{j}$ can be computed prior to many evaluations of $\mathbf {B} (t)$ ; however one should use caution as high order curves may lack numeric stability (de Casteljau's algorithm should be used if this occurs).
[src:nurbs-surfaces/bézier-curve] A quadratic Bézier curve is also a segment of a parabola.
[src:nurbs-surfaces/bézier-curve] As a parabola is a conic section, some sources refer to quadratic Béziers as "conic arcs".
[src:nurbs-surfaces/bézier-curve] If D is the midpoint of AB, the tangent to the curve which is perpendicular to CD (dashed cyan line) defines its vertex (V).
[src:nurbs-surfaces/bézier-curve] Its axis of symmetry (dash-dot cyan) passes through V and is perpendicular to the tangent.
[src:nurbs-surfaces/bézier-curve] E is either point on the curve with a tangent at 45° to CD (dashed green).
[src:nurbs-surfaces/bézier-curve] If G is the intersection of this tangent and the axis, the line passing through G and perpendicular to CD is the directrix (solid green).
[src:nurbs-surfaces/bézier-curve] The focus (F) is at the intersection of the axis and a line passing through E and perpendicular to CD (dotted yellow).
[src:nurbs-surfaces/bézier-curve] The latus rectum is the line segment within the curve (solid yellow).
[src:nurbs-surfaces/bézier-curve] Let *t* denote the fraction of progress (from 0 to 1) the point **B**(*t*) has made along its traversal from **P**0 to **P**1.
[src:nurbs-surfaces/bézier-curve] For higher-order curves one needs correspondingly more intermediate points.
[src:nurbs-surfaces/bézier-curve] For fifth-order curves, one can construct similar intermediate points.
[src:nurbs-surfaces/bézier-curve] These representations rest on the process used in De Casteljau's algorithm to calculate Bézier curves.
[src:nurbs-surfaces/bézier-curve] The curve at a fixed offset from a given Bézier curve, called an offset or parallel curve in mathematics (lying "parallel" to the original curve, like the offset between rails in a railroad track), cannot be exactly formed by a Bézier curve (except in some trivial cases).
[src:nurbs-surfaces/bézier-curve] In general, the two-sided offset curve of a cubic Bézier is a 10th-order algebraic curve and more generally for a Bézier of degree *n* the two-sided offset curve is an algebraic curve of degree 4*n* − 2.
[src:nurbs-surfaces/bézier-curve] However, there are heuristic methods that usually give an adequate approximation for practical purposes.
[src:nurbs-surfaces/bézier-curve] In the field of vector graphics, painting two symmetrically distanced offset curves is called *stroking* (the Bézier curve or in general a path of several Bézier segments).
[src:nurbs-surfaces/bézier-curve] A Bézier curve of degree *n* can be converted into a Bézier curve of degree *n* + 1 *with the same shape*.
[src:nurbs-surfaces/bézier-curve] This is useful if software supports Bézier curves only of specific degree.
[src:nurbs-surfaces/bézier-curve] For example, systems that can only work with cubic Bézier curves can implicitly work with quadratic curves by using their equivalent cubic representation.
[src:nurbs-surfaces/bézier-curve] To do degree elevation, we use the equality $\mathbf {B} (t)=(1-t)\mathbf {B} (t)+t\mathbf {B} (t).$ Each component $\mathbf {b} _{i,n}(t)\mathbf {P} _{i}$ is multiplied by (1 − *t*) and *t*, thus increasing a degree by one, without changing the value.
[src:nurbs-surfaces/bézier-curve] Here is the example of increasing degree from 2 to 3.
[src:nurbs-surfaces/bézier-curve] In other words, the original start and end points are unchanged.
[src:nurbs-surfaces/bézier-curve] The concept of degree elevation can be repeated on a control polygon **R** to get a sequence of control polygons **R**, **R**1, **R**2, and so on.
[src:nurbs-surfaces/bézier-curve] Degree reduction can only be done exactly when the curve in question is originally elevated from a lower degree.
[src:nurbs-surfaces/bézier-curve] A number of approximation algorithms have been proposed and used in practice.
[src:nurbs-surfaces/bézier-curve] The rational Bézier curve adds adjustable weights to provide closer approximations to arbitrary shapes.
[src:nurbs-surfaces/bézier-curve] The numerator is a weighted Bernstein-form Bézier curve and the denominator is a weighted sum of Bernstein polynomials.
[src:nurbs-surfaces/bézier-curve] Rational Bézier curves can, among other uses, be used to represent segments of conic sections exactly, including circular arcs.
[src:nurbs-surfaces/bézier-curve] The expression can be extended by using number systems besides reals for the weights.
[src:nurbs-surfaces/bézier-curve] In the complex plane the points {1}, {-1}, and {1} with weights { i }, {1}, and { $-i$ } generate a full circle with radius one.
[src:nurbs-surfaces/bézier-curve] For curves with points and weights on a circle, the weights can be scaled without changing the curve's shape.
[src:nurbs-surfaces/bézier-curve] Scaling the central weight of the above curve by 1.35508 gives a more uniform parameterization.
[src:nurbs-surfaces/bézier-curve] Bézier curves are widely used in computer graphics to model smooth curves.
[src:nurbs-surfaces/bézier-curve] As the curve is completely contained in the convex hull of its control points, the points can be graphically displayed and used to manipulate the curve intuitively.
[src:nurbs-surfaces/bézier-curve] Affine transformations such as translation and rotation can be applied on the curve by applying the respective transform on the control points of the curve.
[src:nurbs-surfaces/bézier-curve] Quadratic and cubic Bézier curves are most common.
[src:nurbs-surfaces/bézier-curve] Higher degree curves are more computationally expensive to evaluate.
[src:nurbs-surfaces/bézier-curve] When more complex shapes are needed, low order Bézier curves are patched together, producing a composite Bézier curve.
[src:nurbs-surfaces/bézier-curve] A composite Bézier curve is commonly referred to as a "path" in vector graphics languages (like PostScript), vector graphics standards (like SVG) and vector graphics programs (like Artline, Timeworks Publisher, Adobe Illustrator, CorelDraw, Inkscape, and Allegro).
[src:nurbs-surfaces/bézier-curve] In order to join Bézier curves into a composite Bézier curve without kinks, a property called *G1 continuity* suffices to force the control point at which two constituent Bézier curves meet to lie on the line defined by the two control points on either side.
[src:nurbs-surfaces/bézier-curve] The simplest method for scan converting (rasterizing) a Bézier curve is to evaluate it at many closely spaced points and scan convert the approximating sequence of line segments.
[src:nurbs-surfaces/bézier-curve] However, this does not guarantee that the rasterized output looks sufficiently smooth, because the points may be spaced too far apart.
[src:nurbs-surfaces/bézier-curve] Conversely it may generate too many points in areas where the curve is close to linear.
[src:nurbs-surfaces/bézier-curve] A common adaptive method is recursive subdivision, in which a curve's control points are checked to see if the curve approximates a line to within a small tolerance.
[src:nurbs-surfaces/bézier-curve] If not, the curve is subdivided parametrically into two segments, 0 ≤ *t* ≤ 0.5 and 0.5 ≤ *t* ≤ 1, and the same procedure is applied recursively to each half.
[src:nurbs-surfaces/bézier-curve] There are also forward differencing methods, but great care must be taken to analyse error propagation.
[src:nurbs-surfaces/bézier-curve] Analytical methods where a Bézier is intersected with each scan line involve finding roots of cubic polynomials (for cubic Béziers) and dealing with multiple roots, so they are not often used in practice.
[src:nurbs-surfaces/bézier-curve] The rasterisation algorithm used in Metafont is based on discretising the curve, so that it is approximated by a sequence of "rook moves" that are purely vertical or purely horizontal, along the pixel boundaries.
[src:nurbs-surfaces/bézier-curve] This reduces the next step calculation to a series of integer additions and subtractions.
[src:nurbs-surfaces/bézier-curve] In animation applications, such as Adobe Flash and Synfig, Bézier curves are used to outline, for example, movement.
[src:nurbs-surfaces/bézier-curve] Users outline the wanted path in Bézier curves, and the application creates the needed frames for the object to move along the path.
[src:nurbs-surfaces/bézier-curve] In 3D animation, Bézier curves are often used to define 3D paths as well as 2D curves for keyframe interpolation.
[src:nurbs-surfaces/bézier-curve] Bézier curves are now very frequently used to control the animation easing in CSS, JavaScript, JavaFx and Flutter SDK.
[src:nurbs-surfaces/bézier-curve] TrueType fonts use composite Bézier curves composed of quadratic Bézier curves.
[src:nurbs-surfaces/bézier-curve] Other languages and imaging tools (such as PostScript, Asymptote, Metafont, and SVG) use composite Béziers composed of cubic Bézier curves for drawing curved shapes.
[src:nurbs-surfaces/bézier-curve] OpenType fonts can use either kind of curve, depending on which font technology underlies the OpenType wrapper.
[src:nurbs-surfaces/bézier-curve] Font engines, like FreeType, draw the font's curves (and lines) on a pixellated surface using a process known as font rasterization.
[src:nurbs-surfaces/bézier-curve] Typically font engines and vector graphics engines render Bézier curves by splitting them recursively up to the point where the curve is flat enough to be drawn as a series of linear or circular segments.
[src:nurbs-surfaces/bézier-curve] The exact splitting algorithm is implementation dependent, only the flatness criteria must be respected to reach the necessary precision and to avoid non-monotonic local changes of curvature.
[src:nurbs-surfaces/bézier-curve] The "smooth curve" feature of charts in Microsoft Excel also uses this algorithm.
[src:nurbs-surfaces/bézier-curve] Because arcs of circles and ellipses cannot be exactly represented by Bézier curves, they are first approximated by Bézier curves, which are in turn approximated by arcs of circles.
[src:nurbs-surfaces/bézier-curve] This is inefficient as there exists also approximations of all Bézier curves using arcs of circles or ellipses, which can be rendered incrementally with arbitrary precision.
[src:nurbs-surfaces/bézier-curve] Another approach, used by modern hardware graphics adapters with accelerated geometry, can convert exactly all Bézier and conic curves (or surfaces) into NURBS, that can be rendered incrementally without first splitting the curve recursively to reach the necessary flatness condition.
[src:nurbs-surfaces/bézier-curve] This approach also preserves the curve definition under all linear or perspective 2D and 3D transforms and projections.
[src:nurbs-surfaces/bézier-curve] Because the control polygon allows to tell whether or not the path collides with any obstacles, Bézier curves are used in producing trajectories of the end effectors.
[src:nurbs-surfaces/bézier-curve] Furthermore, joint space trajectories can be accurately differentiated using Bézier curves.
[src:nurbs-surfaces/bézier-curve] Consequently, the derivatives of joint space trajectories are used in the calculation of the dynamics and control effort (torque profiles) of the robotic manipulator.
[src:nurbs-surfaces/control-point-mathematics] In computer-aided geometric design a **control point** is a member of a set of points used to determine the shape of a spline curve or, more generally, a surface or higher-dimensional object.
[src:nurbs-surfaces/control-point-mathematics] Some would reasonably insist, in order to give intuitive geometric meaning to the word "control", that the blending functions form a partition of unity, i.e., that the ⁠ $\phi _{i}$ ⁠ are nonnegative and sum to one.
[src:nurbs-surfaces/control-point-mathematics] This property implies that the curve lies within the convex hull of its control points.
[src:nurbs-surfaces/control-point-mathematics] This is the case for Bézier's representation of a polynomial curve as well as for the B-spline representation of a spline curve or tensor-product spline surface.
[src:nurbs-surfaces/non-uniform-rational-b-spline] They can be efficiently handled by computer programs yet allow for easy human interaction.
[src:nurbs-surfaces/non-uniform-rational-b-spline] NURBS surfaces are functions of two parameters mapping to a surface in three-dimensional space.
[src:nurbs-surfaces/non-uniform-rational-b-spline] The shape of the surface is determined by control points.
[src:nurbs-surfaces/non-uniform-rational-b-spline] In a compact form, NURBS surfaces can represent simple geometrical shapes.
[src:nurbs-surfaces/non-uniform-rational-b-spline] For complex organic shapes, T-splines and subdivision surfaces are more suitable because they halve the number of control points in comparison with the NURBS surfaces.
[src:nurbs-surfaces/non-uniform-rational-b-spline] In general, editing NURBS curves and surfaces is intuitive and predictable.
[src:nurbs-surfaces/non-uniform-rational-b-spline] Control points are always either connected directly to the curve or surface, or else act as if they were connected by a rubber band.
[src:nurbs-surfaces/non-uniform-rational-b-spline] Depending on the type of user interface, the editing of NURBS curves and surfaces can be via their control points (similar to Bézier curves) or via higher level tools such as *spline modeling* and *hierarchical editing*.
[src:nurbs-surfaces/non-uniform-rational-b-spline] Before computers, designs were drawn by hand on paper with various drafting tools.
[src:nurbs-surfaces/non-uniform-rational-b-spline] Rulers were used for straight lines, compasses for circles, and protractors for angles.
[src:nurbs-surfaces/non-uniform-rational-b-spline] But many shapes, such as the freeform curve of a ship's bow, could not be drawn with these tools.
[src:nurbs-surfaces/non-uniform-rational-b-spline] Although such curves could be drawn freehand at the drafting board, shipbuilders often needed a life-size version which could not be done by hand.
[src:nurbs-surfaces/non-uniform-rational-b-spline] Such large drawings were done with the help of flexible strips of wood, called splines.
[src:nurbs-surfaces/non-uniform-rational-b-spline] The splines were held in place at a number of predetermined points, by lead "ducks", named for the bill-shaped protrusion that the splines rested against.
[src:nurbs-surfaces/non-uniform-rational-b-spline] Between the ducks, the elasticity of the spline material caused the strip to take the shape that minimized the energy of bending, thus creating the smoothest possible shape that fit the constraints.
[src:nurbs-surfaces/non-uniform-rational-b-spline] The shape could be adjusted by moving the ducks.
[src:nurbs-surfaces/non-uniform-rational-b-spline] In 1964, mathematicians started studying the spline shape, and derived the piecewise polynomial formula known as the spline curve or spline function.
[src:nurbs-surfaces/non-uniform-rational-b-spline] Schoenberg gave the spline function its name after its resemblance to the mechanical spline used by draftsmen.
[src:nurbs-surfaces/non-uniform-rational-b-spline] As computers were introduced into the design process, the physical properties of such splines were investigated so that they could be modelled with mathematical precision and reproduced where needed.
[src:nurbs-surfaces/non-uniform-rational-b-spline] Pioneering work was done in France by Renault engineer Pierre Bézier, and Citroën's physicist and mathematician Paul de Casteljau.
[src:nurbs-surfaces/non-uniform-rational-b-spline] They worked nearly parallel to each other, but because Bézier published the results of his work, Bézier curves were named after him, while de Casteljau's name is only associated with related algorithms.
[src:nurbs-surfaces/non-uniform-rational-b-spline] Bézier's work reached a group of faculty and graduate students at Syracuse University, including Steven Anson Coons, William Gordon, Robin Forrest, Rich Riesenfeld, and Ken Versprille.
[src:nurbs-surfaces/non-uniform-rational-b-spline] Riesenfeld's dissertation introduced B-splines; Versprille's dissertation generalized them to be non-uniform and rational.
[src:nurbs-surfaces/non-uniform-rational-b-spline] Riesenfeld moved to the University of Utah, where one of his students went on to work at Boeing, which needed a generalized way to exactly represent various other formulas in use.
[src:nurbs-surfaces/non-uniform-rational-b-spline] Boeing adopted Versprille's concept, abbreviated it to "NURBS", integrated it into their CAD program TIGER, and proposed it as an industry standard.
[src:nurbs-surfaces/non-uniform-rational-b-spline] Real-time, interactive rendering of NURBS curves and surfaces was first made commercially available on Silicon Graphics workstations in 1989.
[src:nurbs-surfaces/non-uniform-rational-b-spline] In 1993, the first interactive NURBS modeller for PCs, called NöRBS, was developed by CAS Berlin, a small startup company cooperating with Technische Universität Berlin.
[src:nurbs-surfaces/non-uniform-rational-b-spline] A surface under construction, e.g. the hull of a motor yacht, is usually composed of several NURBS surfaces known as **NURBS patches** (or just *patches*).
[src:nurbs-surfaces/non-uniform-rational-b-spline] These surface patches should be fitted together in such a way that the boundaries are invisible.
[src:nurbs-surfaces/non-uniform-rational-b-spline] This is mathematically expressed by the concept of geometric continuity.
[src:nurbs-surfaces/non-uniform-rational-b-spline] ) holds whenever the end positions of two curves or surfaces coincide.
[src:nurbs-surfaces/non-uniform-rational-b-spline] The curves or surfaces may still meet at an angle, giving rise to a sharp corner or edge and causing broken highlights.
[src:nurbs-surfaces/non-uniform-rational-b-spline] (G¹) requires the end vectors of the curves or surfaces to be parallel and pointing the same way, ruling out sharp edges.
[src:nurbs-surfaces/non-uniform-rational-b-spline] Because highlights falling on a tangentially continuous edge are always continuous and thus look natural, this level of continuity can often be sufficient.
[src:nurbs-surfaces/non-uniform-rational-b-spline] (G²) further requires the end vectors to be of the same length and rate of length change.
[src:nurbs-surfaces/non-uniform-rational-b-spline] Highlights falling on a curvature-continuous edge do not display any change, causing the two surfaces to appear as one.
[src:nurbs-surfaces/non-uniform-rational-b-spline] This can be visually recognized as "perfectly smooth".
[src:nurbs-surfaces/non-uniform-rational-b-spline] patches composing one continuous surface.
[src:nurbs-surfaces/non-uniform-rational-b-spline] Geometric continuity mainly refers to the shape of the resulting surface; since NURBS surfaces are functions, it is also possible to discuss the derivatives of the surface with respect to the parameters.
[src:nurbs-surfaces/non-uniform-rational-b-spline] Parametric continuity of a given degree implies geometric continuity of that degree.
[src:nurbs-surfaces/non-uniform-rational-b-spline] First- and second-level parametric continuity (C0 and C¹) are for practical purposes identical to positional and tangential (G0 and G¹) continuity.
[src:nurbs-surfaces/non-uniform-rational-b-spline] Third-level parametric continuity (C²), however, differs from curvature continuity in that its parameterization is also continuous.
[src:nurbs-surfaces/non-uniform-rational-b-spline] In practice, C² continuity is easier to achieve if uniform B-splines are used.
[src:nurbs-surfaces/non-uniform-rational-b-spline] The definition of C*n* continuity requires that the *n*th derivative of adjacent curves/surfaces ( $d^{n}C(u)/du^{n}$ ) are equal at a joint.
[src:nurbs-surfaces/non-uniform-rational-b-spline] Note that the (partial) derivatives of curves and surfaces are vectors that have a direction and a magnitude; both should be equal.
[src:nurbs-surfaces/non-uniform-rational-b-spline] Highlights and reflections can reveal the perfect smoothing, which is otherwise practically impossible to achieve without NURBS surfaces that have at least G² continuity.
[src:nurbs-surfaces/non-uniform-rational-b-spline] This same principle is used as one of the surface evaluation methods whereby a ray-traced or reflection-mapped image of a surface with white stripes reflecting on it will show even the smallest deviations on a surface or set of surfaces.
[src:nurbs-surfaces/non-uniform-rational-b-spline] This method is derived from car prototyping wherein surface quality is inspected by checking the quality of reflections of a neon-light ceiling on the car surface.
[src:nurbs-surfaces/non-uniform-rational-b-spline] This method is also known as "Zebra analysis".
[src:nurbs-surfaces/non-uniform-rational-b-spline] A NURBS curve is defined by its order, a set of weighted control points, and a knot vector.
[src:nurbs-surfaces/non-uniform-rational-b-spline] NURBS curves and surfaces are generalizations of both B-splines and Bézier curves and surfaces, the primary difference being the weighting of the control points, which makes NURBS curves *rational*.
[src:nurbs-surfaces/non-uniform-rational-b-spline] (*Non-rational*, aka *simple*, B-splines are a special case/subset of rational B-splines, where each control point is a regular non-homogenous coordinate [no 'w'] rather than a homogeneous coordinate.
[src:nurbs-surfaces/non-uniform-rational-b-spline] By using a two-dimensional grid of control points, NURBS surfaces including planar patches and sections of spheres can be created.
[src:nurbs-surfaces/non-uniform-rational-b-spline] These are parametrized with two variables (typically called *s* and *t* or *u* and *v*).
[src:nurbs-surfaces/non-uniform-rational-b-spline] This can be extended to arbitrary dimensions to create NURBS mapping $\mathbb {R} ^{n}\to \mathbb {R} ^{n}$ .
[src:nurbs-surfaces/non-uniform-rational-b-spline] Here, NURBS is mostly discussed in one dimension (curves); it can be generalized to two (surfaces) or even more dimensions.
[src:nurbs-surfaces/non-uniform-rational-b-spline] The *order* of a NURBS curve defines the number of nearby control points that influence any given point on the curve.
[src:nurbs-surfaces/non-uniform-rational-b-spline] The curve is represented mathematically by a polynomial of degree one less than the order of the curve.
[src:nurbs-surfaces/non-uniform-rational-b-spline] Hence, second-order curves (which are represented by linear polynomials) are called linear curves, third-order curves are called quadratic curves, and fourth-order curves are called cubic curves.
[src:nurbs-surfaces/non-uniform-rational-b-spline] The number of control points must be greater than or equal to the order of the curve.
[src:nurbs-surfaces/non-uniform-rational-b-spline] In practice, cubic curves are the ones most commonly used.
[src:nurbs-surfaces/non-uniform-rational-b-spline] Fifth- and sixth-order curves are sometimes useful, especially for obtaining continuous higher order derivatives, but curves of higher orders are practically never used because they lead to internal numerical problems and tend to require disproportionately large calculation times.
[src:nurbs-surfaces/non-uniform-rational-b-spline] The control points determine the shape of the curve.
[src:nurbs-surfaces/non-uniform-rational-b-spline] Typically, each point of the curve is computed by taking a weighted sum of a number of control points.
[src:nurbs-surfaces/non-uniform-rational-b-spline] For a curve of degree d, the weight of any control point is only nonzero in d+1 intervals of the parameter space.
[src:nurbs-surfaces/non-uniform-rational-b-spline] Within those intervals, the weight changes according to a polynomial function (*basis functions*) of degree d.
[src:nurbs-surfaces/non-uniform-rational-b-spline] As an example, the basis function of degree one is a triangle function.
[src:nurbs-surfaces/non-uniform-rational-b-spline] It rises from zero to one, then falls to zero again.
[src:nurbs-surfaces/non-uniform-rational-b-spline] While it rises, the basis function of the previous control point falls.
[src:nurbs-surfaces/non-uniform-rational-b-spline] In that way, the curve interpolates between the two points, and the resulting curve is a polygon, which is continuous, but not differentiable at the interval boundaries, or knots.
[src:nurbs-surfaces/non-uniform-rational-b-spline] Higher degree polynomials have correspondingly more continuous derivatives.
[src:nurbs-surfaces/non-uniform-rational-b-spline] Note that within the interval the polynomial nature of the basis functions and the linearity of the construction make the curve perfectly smooth, so it is only at the knots that discontinuity can arise.
[src:nurbs-surfaces/non-uniform-rational-b-spline] In many applications the fact that a single control point only influences those intervals where it is active is a highly desirable property, known as **local support**.
[src:nurbs-surfaces/non-uniform-rational-b-spline] In modeling, it allows the changing of one part of a surface while keeping other parts unchanged.
[src:nurbs-surfaces/non-uniform-rational-b-spline] Adding more control points allows better approximation to a given curve, although only a certain class of curves can be represented exactly with a finite number of control points.
[src:nurbs-surfaces/non-uniform-rational-b-spline] NURBS curves also feature a scalar **weight** for each control point.
[src:nurbs-surfaces/non-uniform-rational-b-spline] This allows for more control over the shape of the curve without unduly raising the number of control points.
[src:nurbs-surfaces/non-uniform-rational-b-spline] In particular, it adds conic sections like circles and ellipses to the set of curves that can be represented exactly.
[src:nurbs-surfaces/non-uniform-rational-b-spline] The term *rational* in NURBS refers to these weights.
[src:nurbs-surfaces/non-uniform-rational-b-spline] The control points can have any dimensionality.
[src:nurbs-surfaces/non-uniform-rational-b-spline] One-dimensional points just define a scalar function of the parameter.
[src:nurbs-surfaces/non-uniform-rational-b-spline] These are typically used in image processing programs to tune the brightness and color curves.
[src:nurbs-surfaces/non-uniform-rational-b-spline] Three-dimensional control points are used abundantly in 3D modeling, where they are used in the everyday meaning of the word 'point', a location in 3D space.
[src:nurbs-surfaces/non-uniform-rational-b-spline] Multi-dimensional points might be used to control sets of time-driven values, e.g. the different positional and rotational settings of a robot arm.
[src:nurbs-surfaces/non-uniform-rational-b-spline] NURBS surfaces are just an application of this.
[src:nurbs-surfaces/non-uniform-rational-b-spline] Each control 'point' is actually a full vector of control points, defining a curve.
[src:nurbs-surfaces/non-uniform-rational-b-spline] These curves share their degree and the number of control points, and span one dimension of the parameter space.
[src:nurbs-surfaces/non-uniform-rational-b-spline] By interpolating these control vectors over the other dimension of the parameter space, a continuous set of curves is obtained, defining the surface.
[src:nurbs-surfaces/non-uniform-rational-b-spline] The number of knots is always equal to the number of control points plus curve degree plus one (i.e. number of control points plus curve order).
[src:nurbs-surfaces/non-uniform-rational-b-spline] The knot vector divides the parametric space in the intervals mentioned before, usually referred to as *knot spans*.
[src:nurbs-surfaces/non-uniform-rational-b-spline] It follows that the values in the knot vector should be in nondecreasing order, so (0, 0, 1, 2, 3, 3) is valid while (0, 0, 2, 1, 3, 3) is not.
[src:nurbs-surfaces/non-uniform-rational-b-spline] Consecutive knots can have the same value.
[src:nurbs-surfaces/non-uniform-rational-b-spline] This then defines a knot span of zero length, which implies that two control points are activated at the same time (and of course two control points become deactivated).
[src:nurbs-surfaces/non-uniform-rational-b-spline] This has impact on continuity of the resulting curve or its higher derivatives; for instance, it allows the creation of corners in an otherwise smooth NURBS curve.
[src:nurbs-surfaces/non-uniform-rational-b-spline] A number of coinciding knots is sometimes referred to as a knot with a certain **multiplicity**.
[src:nurbs-surfaces/non-uniform-rational-b-spline] Knots with multiplicity two or three are known as double or triple knots.
[src:nurbs-surfaces/non-uniform-rational-b-spline] The multiplicity of a knot is limited to the degree of the curve; since a higher multiplicity would split the curve into disjoint parts and it would leave control points unused.
[src:nurbs-surfaces/non-uniform-rational-b-spline] For first-degree NURBS, each knot is paired with a control point.
[src:nurbs-surfaces/non-uniform-rational-b-spline] The knot vector usually starts with a knot that has multiplicity equal to the order.
[src:nurbs-surfaces/non-uniform-rational-b-spline] This makes sense, since this activates the control points that have influence on the first knot span.
[src:nurbs-surfaces/non-uniform-rational-b-spline] Similarly, the knot vector usually ends with a knot of that multiplicity.
[src:nurbs-surfaces/non-uniform-rational-b-spline] Curves with such knot vectors start and end in a control point.
[src:nurbs-surfaces/non-uniform-rational-b-spline] The values of the knots control the mapping between the input parameter and the corresponding NURBS value.
[src:nurbs-surfaces/non-uniform-rational-b-spline] For example, if a NURBS describes a path through space over time, the knots control the time that the function proceeds past the control points.
[src:nurbs-surfaces/non-uniform-rational-b-spline] For the purposes of representing shapes, however, only the ratios of the difference between the knot values matter; in that case, the knot vectors (0, 0, 1, 2, 3, 3) and (0, 0, 2, 4, 6, 6) produce the same curve.
[src:nurbs-surfaces/non-uniform-rational-b-spline] The positions of the knot values influences the mapping of parameter space to curve space.
[src:nurbs-surfaces/non-uniform-rational-b-spline] Rendering a NURBS curve is usually done by stepping with a fixed stride through the parameter range.
[src:nurbs-surfaces/non-uniform-rational-b-spline] By changing the knot span lengths, more sample points can be used in regions where the curvature is high.
[src:nurbs-surfaces/non-uniform-rational-b-spline] Another use is in situations where the parameter value has some physical significance, for instance if the parameter is time and the curve describes the motion of a robot arm.
[src:nurbs-surfaces/non-uniform-rational-b-spline] The knot span lengths then translate into velocity and acceleration, which are essential to get right to prevent damage to the robot arm or its environment.
[src:nurbs-surfaces/non-uniform-rational-b-spline] This flexibility in the mapping is what the phrase *non uniform* in NURBS refers to.
[src:nurbs-surfaces/non-uniform-rational-b-spline] Necessary only for internal calculations, knots are usually not helpful to the users of modeling software.
[src:nurbs-surfaces/non-uniform-rational-b-spline] Therefore, many modeling applications do not make the knots editable or even visible.
[src:nurbs-surfaces/non-uniform-rational-b-spline] It's usually possible to establish reasonable knot vectors by looking at the variation in the control points.
[src:nurbs-surfaces/non-uniform-rational-b-spline] More recent versions of NURBS software (e.g., Autodesk Maya and Rhinoceros 3D) allow for interactive editing of knot positions, but this is significantly less intuitive than the editing of control points.
[src:nurbs-surfaces/non-uniform-rational-b-spline] The B-spline basis functions used in the construction of NURBS curves are usually denoted as $N_{i,n}(u)$ , in which i corresponds to the i -th control point, and n corresponds with the degree of the basis function.
[src:nurbs-surfaces/non-uniform-rational-b-spline] The parameter dependence is frequently left out, so we can write $N_{i,n}$ .
[src:nurbs-surfaces/non-uniform-rational-b-spline] The definition of these basis functions is recursive in n .
[src:nurbs-surfaces/non-uniform-rational-b-spline] The degree-0 functions $N_{i,0}$ are piecewise constant functions.
[src:nurbs-surfaces/non-uniform-rational-b-spline] They are one on the corresponding knot span and zero everywhere else.
[src:nurbs-surfaces/non-uniform-rational-b-spline] The latter two functions are non-zero for n knot spans, overlapping for $n-1$ knot spans.
[src:nurbs-surfaces/non-uniform-rational-b-spline] As mentioned before, $N_{i,1}$ is a triangular function, nonzero over two knot spans rising from zero to one on the first, and falling to zero on the second knot span.
[src:nurbs-surfaces/non-uniform-rational-b-spline] Higher order basis functions are non-zero over corresponding more knot spans and have correspondingly higher degree.
[src:nurbs-surfaces/non-uniform-rational-b-spline] By induction on n it follows that the basis functions are non-negative for all values of n and u .
[src:nurbs-surfaces/non-uniform-rational-b-spline] This makes the computation of the basis functions numerically stable.
[src:nurbs-surfaces/non-uniform-rational-b-spline] Again by induction, it can be proved that the sum of the basis functions for a particular value of the parameter is unity.
[src:nurbs-surfaces/non-uniform-rational-b-spline] This is known as the **partition of unity** property of the basis functions.
[src:nurbs-surfaces/non-uniform-rational-b-spline] One knot span is considerably shorter than the others.
[src:nurbs-surfaces/non-uniform-rational-b-spline] On that knot span, the peak in the quadratic basis function is more distinct, reaching almost one.
[src:nurbs-surfaces/non-uniform-rational-b-spline] Conversely, the adjoining basis functions fall to zero more quickly.
[src:nurbs-surfaces/non-uniform-rational-b-spline] In the geometrical interpretation, this means that the curve approaches the corresponding control point closely.
[src:nurbs-surfaces/non-uniform-rational-b-spline] In case of a double knot, the length of the knot span becomes zero and the peak reaches one exactly.
[src:nurbs-surfaces/non-uniform-rational-b-spline] The basis function is no longer differentiable at that point.
[src:nurbs-surfaces/non-uniform-rational-b-spline] The curve will have a sharp corner if the neighbour control points are not collinear.
[src:nurbs-surfaces/non-uniform-rational-b-spline] In this, k is the number of control points $\mathbf {P} _{i}$ and $w_{i}$ are the corresponding weights.
[src:nurbs-surfaces/non-uniform-rational-b-spline] This can be seen from the partition of unity property of the basis functions.
[src:nurbs-surfaces/non-uniform-rational-b-spline] A number of transformations can be applied to a NURBS object.
[src:nurbs-surfaces/non-uniform-rational-b-spline] For instance, if some curve is defined using a certain degree and N control points, the same curve can be expressed using the same degree and N+1 control points.
[src:nurbs-surfaces/non-uniform-rational-b-spline] In the process a number of control points change position and a knot is inserted in the knot vector.
[src:nurbs-surfaces/non-uniform-rational-b-spline] These manipulations are used extensively during interactive design.
[src:nurbs-surfaces/non-uniform-rational-b-spline] When adding a control point, the shape of the curve should stay the same, forming the starting point for further adjustments.
[src:nurbs-surfaces/non-uniform-rational-b-spline] A number of these operations are discussed below.
[src:nurbs-surfaces/non-uniform-rational-b-spline] As the term suggests, **knot insertion** inserts a knot into the knot vector.
[src:nurbs-surfaces/non-uniform-rational-b-spline] If the degree of the curve is n , then $n-1$ control points are replaced by n new ones.
[src:nurbs-surfaces/non-uniform-rational-b-spline] A knot can be inserted multiple times, up to the maximum multiplicity of the knot.
[src:nurbs-surfaces/non-uniform-rational-b-spline] This is sometimes referred to as **knot refinement** and can be achieved by an algorithm that is more efficient than repeated knot insertion.
[src:nurbs-surfaces/non-uniform-rational-b-spline] A NURBS curve of a particular degree can always be represented by a NURBS curve of higher degree.
[src:nurbs-surfaces/non-uniform-rational-b-spline] This is frequently used when combining separate NURBS curves, e.g., when creating a NURBS surface interpolating between a set of NURBS curves or when unifying adjacent curves.
[src:nurbs-surfaces/non-uniform-rational-b-spline] In the process, the different curves should be brought to the same degree, usually the maximum degree of the set of curves.
[src:nurbs-surfaces/non-uniform-rational-b-spline] The process is known as **degree elevation**.
[src:nurbs-surfaces/non-uniform-rational-b-spline] The most important property in differential geometry is the curvature $\kappa$ .
[src:nurbs-surfaces/non-uniform-rational-b-spline] It describes the local properties (edges, corners, etc.) and relations between the first and second derivative, and thus, the precise curve shape.
[src:nurbs-surfaces/non-uniform-rational-b-spline] Having determined the derivatives it is easy to compute $\kappa ={\frac {|r'(t)\times r''(t)|}{|r'(t)|^{3}}}$ or approximated as the arclength from the second derivative $\kappa =|r''(s_{o})|$ .
[src:nurbs-surfaces/non-uniform-rational-b-spline] The direct computation of the curvature $\kappa$ with these equations is the big advantage of parameterized curves against their polygonal representations.
[src:nurbs-surfaces/non-uniform-rational-b-spline] Non-rational splines or Bézier curves may approximate a circle, but they cannot represent it exactly.
[src:nurbs-surfaces/non-uniform-rational-b-spline] Rational splines can represent any conic section—including the circle—exactly.
[src:nurbs-surfaces/non-uniform-rational-b-spline] The order is three, since a circle is a quadratic curve and the spline's order is one more than the degree of its piecewise polynomial segments.
[src:nurbs-surfaces/non-uniform-rational-b-spline] The circle is composed of four quarter circles, tied together with double knots.
[src:nurbs-surfaces/non-uniform-rational-b-spline] Although double knots in a third order NURBS curve would normally result in loss of continuity in the first derivative, the control points are positioned in such a way that the first derivative is continuous.
[src:nurbs-surfaces/non-uniform-rational-b-spline] In fact, the curve is infinitely differentiable everywhere, as it must be if it exactly represents a circle.
[src:nurbs-surfaces/non-uniform-rational-b-spline] The curve represents a circle exactly, but it is not exactly parametrized in the circle's arc length.
[src:nurbs-surfaces/non-uniform-rational-b-spline] This means, for example, that the point at t does not lie at $(\sin(t),\cos(t))$ (except for the start, middle and end point of each quarter circle, since the representation is symmetrical).
[src:nurbs-surfaces/non-uniform-rational-b-spline] This would be impossible, since the *x* coordinate of the circle would provide an exact rational polynomial expression for $\cos(t)$ , which is impossible.
[src:nurbs-surfaces/non-uniform-rational-b-spline] The circle does make one full revolution as its parameter t goes from 0 to $2\pi$ , but this is only because the knot vector was arbitrarily chosen as multiples of $\pi /2$ .
[src:nurbs-surfaces/spline-mathematics] In mathematics, a **spline** is a function defined piecewise by polynomials.
[src:nurbs-surfaces/spline-mathematics] In interpolating problems, spline interpolation is often preferred to polynomial interpolation because it yields similar results, even when using low degree polynomials, while avoiding Runge's phenomenon for higher degrees.
[src:nurbs-surfaces/spline-mathematics] In the computer science subfields of computer-aided design and computer graphics, the term *spline* more frequently refers to a piecewise polynomial (parametric) curve.
[src:nurbs-surfaces/spline-mathematics] Splines are popular curves in these subfields because of the simplicity of their construction, their ease and accuracy of evaluation, and their capacity to approximate complex shapes through curve fitting and interactive curve design.
[src:nurbs-surfaces/spline-mathematics] The term spline comes from the flexible spline devices used by shipbuilders and draftsmen to draw smooth shapes.
[src:nurbs-surfaces/spline-mathematics] The term "spline" is used to refer to a wide class of functions that are used in applications requiring data interpolation and/or smoothing.
[src:nurbs-surfaces/spline-mathematics] The data may be either one-dimensional or multi-dimensional.
[src:nurbs-surfaces/spline-mathematics] Spline functions for interpolation are normally determined as the minimizers of suitable measures of roughness (for example integral squared curvature) subject to the interpolation constraints.
[src:nurbs-surfaces/spline-mathematics] Smoothing splines may be viewed as generalizations of interpolation splines where the functions are determined to minimize a weighted combination of the average squared approximation error over observed data and the roughness measure.
[src:nurbs-surfaces/spline-mathematics] For a number of meaningful definitions of the roughness measure, the spline functions are found to be finite dimensional in nature, which is the primary reason for their utility in computations and representation.
[src:nurbs-surfaces/spline-mathematics] For the rest of this section, we focus entirely on one-dimensional, polynomial splines and use the term "spline" in this restricted sense.
[src:nurbs-surfaces/spline-mathematics] According to Gerald Farin, B-splines were explored as early as the nineteenth century by Nikolai Lobachevsky at Kazan University in Russia.
[src:nurbs-surfaces/spline-mathematics] Before computers were used, numerical calculations were done by hand.
[src:nurbs-surfaces/spline-mathematics] Although piecewise-defined functions like the sign function or step function were used, polynomials were generally preferred because they were easier to work with.
[src:nurbs-surfaces/spline-mathematics] Through the advent of computers, splines have gained importance.
[src:nurbs-surfaces/spline-mathematics] They were first used as a replacement for polynomials in interpolation, then as a tool to construct smooth and flexible shapes in computer graphics.
[src:nurbs-surfaces/spline-mathematics] It is commonly accepted that the first mathematical reference to splines is the 1946 paper by Schoenberg, which is probably the first place that the word "spline" is used in connection with smooth, piecewise polynomial approximation.
[src:nurbs-surfaces/spline-mathematics] However, the ideas have their roots in the aircraft and shipbuilding industries.
[src:nurbs-surfaces/spline-mathematics] For years the practice of ship design had employed models to design in the small.
[src:nurbs-surfaces/spline-mathematics] The successful design was then plotted on graph paper and the key points of the plot were re-plotted on larger graph paper to full size.
[src:nurbs-surfaces/spline-mathematics] The thin wooden strips provided an interpolation of the key points into smooth curves.
[src:nurbs-surfaces/spline-mathematics] The strips would be held in place at discrete points (called "ducks" by Forrest; Schoenberg used "dogs" or "rats") and between these points would assume shapes of minimum strain energy.
[src:nurbs-surfaces/spline-mathematics] According to Forrest, one possible impetus for a mathematical model for this process was the potential loss of the critical design components for an entire aircraft should the loft be hit by an enemy bomb.
[src:nurbs-surfaces/spline-mathematics] This gave rise to "conic lofting", which used conic sections to model the position of the curve between the ducks.
[src:nurbs-surfaces/spline-mathematics] Conic lofting was replaced by what we would call splines in the early 1960s based on work by J.
[src:nurbs-surfaces/spline-mathematics] Ferguson at Boeing and (somewhat later) by Malcolm A.
[src:nurbs-surfaces/spline-mathematics] The word "spline" was originally an East Anglian dialect word.
[src:nurbs-surfaces/spline-mathematics] The use of splines for modeling automobile bodies seems to have several independent beginnings.
[src:nurbs-surfaces/spline-mathematics] Credit is claimed on behalf of de Casteljau at Citroën, Pierre Bézier at Renault, and Birkhoff, Garabedian, and de Boor at General Motors (see Birkhoff and de Boor, 1965), all for work occurring in the very early 1960s or late 1950s.
[src:nurbs-surfaces/spline-mathematics] At least one of de Casteljau's papers was published, but not widely, in 1959.
[src:nurbs-surfaces/spline-mathematics] De Boor's work at General Motors resulted in a number of papers being published in the early 1960s, including some of the fundamental work on B-splines.
[src:nurbs-surfaces/spline-mathematics] Work was also being done at Pratt & Whitney Aircraft, where two of the authors of (Ahlberg et al., 1967) — the first book-length treatment of splines — were employed, and the David Taylor Model Basin, by Feodor Theilheimer.
[src:nurbs-surfaces/spline-mathematics] The work at General Motors is detailed nicely in (Birkhoff, 1990) and (Young, 1997).
[src:nurbs-surfaces/spline-mathematics] Davis (1997) summarizes some of this material.
[src:nurbs-surfaces/spline-mathematics] We begin by limiting our discussion to polynomials in one variable.
[src:nurbs-surfaces/spline-mathematics] In this case, a spline is a piecewise polynomial function.
[src:nurbs-surfaces/spline-mathematics] This function, call it S, takes values from an interval [*a*,*b*] and maps them to $\mathbb {R} ,$ the set of real numbers, $S:[a,b]\to \mathbb {R} .$ We want S to be piecewise defined.
[src:nurbs-surfaces/spline-mathematics] The given *k* + 1 points ti are called **knots**.
[src:nurbs-surfaces/spline-mathematics] The vector **t** = (*t*0, …, *tk*) is called a **knot vector** for the spline.
[src:nurbs-surfaces/spline-mathematics] If the knots are equidistantly distributed in the interval [*a*,*b*] we say the spline is **uniform**, otherwise we say it is **non-uniform**.
[src:nurbs-surfaces/spline-mathematics] If the polynomial pieces Pi each have degree at most n, then the spline is said to be of **degree** ≤ *n* (or of **order** *n* + 1).
[src:nurbs-surfaces/spline-mathematics] If $S\in C^{r_{i}}$ in a neighborhood of ti, then the spline is said to be of smoothness (at least) $C^{r_{i}}$ at ti.
[src:nurbs-surfaces/spline-mathematics] A vector **r** = (*r*1, …, *r**k*–1) such that the spline has smoothness $C^{r_{i}}$ at ti for *i* = 1, …, *k* – 1 is called a **smoothness vector** for the spline.
[src:nurbs-surfaces/spline-mathematics] Given a knot vector **t**, a degree n, and a smoothness vector **r** for **t**, one can consider the set of all splines of degree ≤ *n* having knot vector **t** and smoothness vector **r**.
[src:nurbs-surfaces/spline-mathematics] Equipped with the operation of adding two functions (pointwise addition) and taking real multiples of functions, this set becomes a real vector space.
[src:nurbs-surfaces/spline-mathematics] In the mathematical study of polynomial splines the question of what happens when two knots, say ti and *t**i*+1, are taken to approach one another and become coincident has an easy answer.
[src:nurbs-surfaces/spline-mathematics] The polynomial piece *Pi*(*t*) disappears, and the pieces *P**i*−1(*t*) and *P**i*+1(*t*) join with the sum of the smoothness losses for ti and *t**i*+1.
[src:nurbs-surfaces/spline-mathematics] This leads to a more general understanding of a knot vector.
[src:nurbs-surfaces/spline-mathematics] where ti is repeated ji times for *i* = 1, …, *k* – 1.
[src:nurbs-surfaces/spline-mathematics] A parametric curve on the interval [*a*,*b*] $G(t)={\bigl (}X(t),Y(t){\bigr )},\quad t\in [a,b]$ is a **spline curve** if both X and Y are spline functions of the same degree with the same extended knot vectors on that interval.
[src:nurbs-surfaces/spline-mathematics] Suppose the polynomial pieces are to be of degree 2, and the pieces on [0, 1] and [1, 2] must join in value and first derivative (at *t* = 1) while the pieces on [1, 2] and [2, 3] join simply in value (at *t* = 2).
[src:nurbs-surfaces/spline-mathematics] (Note: while the polynomial piece 2*t* is not quadratic, the result is still called a quadratic spline.
[src:nurbs-surfaces/spline-mathematics] This demonstrates that the degree of a spline is the maximum degree of its polynomial parts.) The extended knot vector for this type of spline would be (0, 1, 2, 2, 3).
[src:nurbs-surfaces/spline-mathematics] The next most simple spline has degree 1.
[src:nurbs-surfaces/spline-mathematics] A closed linear spline (i.e, the first knot and the last are the same) in the plane is just a polygon.
[src:nurbs-surfaces/spline-mathematics] A common spline is the **natural cubic spline**.
[src:nurbs-surfaces/spline-mathematics] A cubic spline has degree 3 with continuity *C*2, i.e. the values and first and second derivatives are continuous.
[src:nurbs-surfaces/spline-mathematics] Natural means that the second derivatives of the spline polynomials are zero at the endpoints of the interval of interpolation.
[src:nurbs-surfaces/spline-mathematics] Thus, the graph of the spline is a straight line outside of the interval, but still smooth.
[src:nurbs-surfaces/surface-mathematics] In mathematics, a **surface** is a mathematical model of the common concept of a surface.
[src:nurbs-surfaces/surface-mathematics] It is a generalization of a plane, but, unlike a plane, it may be curved (this is analogous to a curve generalizing a straight line).
[src:nurbs-surfaces/surface-mathematics] An example of a non-flat surface is the sphere.
[src:nurbs-surfaces/surface-mathematics] There are several more precise definitions, depending on the context and the mathematical tools that are used for the study.
[src:nurbs-surfaces/surface-mathematics] The simplest mathematical surfaces are planes and spheres in the Euclidean 3-space.
[src:nurbs-surfaces/surface-mathematics] Typically, in algebraic geometry, a surface may cross itself (and may have other singularities), while, in topology and differential geometry, it may not.
[src:nurbs-surfaces/surface-mathematics] A surface is a topological space of dimension two; this means that a moving point on a surface may move in two directions (it has two degrees of freedom).
[src:nurbs-surfaces/surface-mathematics] In other words, around almost every point, there is a *coordinate patch* on which a two-dimensional coordinate system is defined.
[src:nurbs-surfaces/surface-mathematics] For example, the surface of the Earth resembles (ideally) a sphere, and latitude and longitude provide two-dimensional coordinates on it (except at the poles and along the 180th meridian).
[src:nurbs-surfaces/surface-mathematics] Often, a surface is defined by equations that are satisfied by the coordinates of its points.
[src:nurbs-surfaces/surface-mathematics] This is the case for the graph of a continuous function of two variables.
[src:nurbs-surfaces/surface-mathematics] The set of the zeros of a function of three variables is a surface, which is called an implicit surface.
[src:nurbs-surfaces/surface-mathematics] If the defining three-variable function is a polynomial, the surface is an algebraic surface.
[src:nurbs-surfaces/surface-mathematics] A surface may also be defined as the image, in some space of dimension at least 3, of a continuous function of two variables (some further conditions are required to ensure that the image is not a curve).
[src:nurbs-surfaces/surface-mathematics] In this case, one says that one has a parametric surface, which is *parametrized* by these two variables, called *parameters*.
[src:nurbs-surfaces/surface-mathematics] Parametric equations of surfaces are often irregular at some points.
[src:nurbs-surfaces/surface-mathematics] For example, all but two points of the unit sphere, are the image, by the above parametrization, of exactly one pair of Euler angles (modulo 2π).
[src:nurbs-surfaces/surface-mathematics] For the remaining two points (the north and south poles), one has cos *v* = 0, and the longitude *u* may take any values.
[src:nurbs-surfaces/surface-mathematics] Also, there are surfaces for which there cannot exist a single parametrization that covers the whole surface.
[src:nurbs-surfaces/surface-mathematics] Therefore, one often considers surfaces which are parametrized by several parametric equations, whose images cover the surface.
[src:nurbs-surfaces/surface-mathematics] This allows defining surfaces in spaces of dimension higher than three, and even *abstract surfaces*, which are not contained in any other space.
[src:nurbs-surfaces/surface-mathematics] On the other hand, this excludes surfaces that have singularities, such as the vertex of a conical surface or points where a surface crosses itself.
[src:nurbs-surfaces/surface-mathematics] In classical geometry, a surface is generally defined as a locus of a point or a line.
[src:nurbs-surfaces/surface-mathematics] For example, a sphere is the locus of a point which is at a given distance of a fixed point, called the center; a conical surface is the locus of a line passing through a fixed point and crossing a curve; a surface of revolution is the locus of a curve rotating around a line.
[src:nurbs-surfaces/surface-mathematics] A ruled surface is the locus of a moving line satisfying some constraints; in modern terminology, a ruled surface is a surface, which is a union of lines.
[src:nurbs-surfaces/surface-mathematics] There are several kinds of surfaces that are considered in mathematics.
[src:nurbs-surfaces/surface-mathematics] An unambiguous terminology is thus necessary to distinguish them when needed.
[src:nurbs-surfaces/surface-mathematics] A *topological surface* is a surface that is a manifold of dimension two (see § Topological surface).
[src:nurbs-surfaces/surface-mathematics] A *differentiable surface* is a surfaces that is a differentiable manifold (see § Differentiable surface).
[src:nurbs-surfaces/surface-mathematics] Every differentiable surface is a topological surface, but the converse is false.
[src:nurbs-surfaces/surface-mathematics] A "surface" is often implicitly supposed to be contained in a Euclidean space of dimension 3, typically **R**3.
[src:nurbs-surfaces/surface-mathematics] A surface that is contained in a projective space is called a projective surface (see § Projective surface).
[src:nurbs-surfaces/surface-mathematics] A surface that is not supposed to be included in another space is called an *abstract surface*.
[src:nurbs-surfaces/surface-mathematics] A **parametric surface** is the image of an open subset of the Euclidean plane (typically $\mathbb {R} ^{2}$ ) by a continuous function, in a topological space, generally a Euclidean space of dimension at least three.
[src:nurbs-surfaces/surface-mathematics] Usually the function is supposed to be continuously differentiable, and this will be always the case in this article.
[src:nurbs-surfaces/surface-mathematics] Here "almost all" means that the values of the parameters where the rank is two contain a dense open subset of the range of the parametrization.
[src:nurbs-surfaces/surface-mathematics] For surfaces in a space of higher dimension, the condition is the same, except for the number of columns of the Jacobian matrix.
[src:nurbs-surfaces/surface-mathematics] A point p where the above Jacobian matrix has rank two is called *regular*, or, more properly, the parametrization is called *regular* at p.
[src:nurbs-surfaces/surface-mathematics] The *tangent plane* at a regular point p is the unique plane passing through p and having a direction parallel to the two row vectors of the Jacobian matrix.
[src:nurbs-surfaces/surface-mathematics] The tangent plane is an affine concept, because its definition is independent of the choice of a metric.
[src:nurbs-surfaces/surface-mathematics] In other words, any affine transformation maps the tangent plane to the surface at a point to the tangent plane to the image of the surface at the image of the point.
[src:nurbs-surfaces/surface-mathematics] The *normal line* at a point of a surface is the unique line passing through the point and perpendicular to the tangent plane; a *normal vector* is a vector which is parallel to the normal line.
[src:nurbs-surfaces/surface-mathematics] For other differential invariants of surfaces, in the neighborhood of a point, see Differential geometry of surfaces.
[src:nurbs-surfaces/surface-mathematics] A point of a parametric surface which is not regular is **irregular**.
[src:nurbs-surfaces/surface-mathematics] There are several kinds of irregular points.
[src:nurbs-surfaces/surface-mathematics] It may occur that an irregular point becomes regular, if one changes the parametrization.
[src:nurbs-surfaces/surface-mathematics] This is the case of the poles in the parametrization of the unit sphere by Euler angles: it suffices to permute the role of the different coordinate axes for changing the poles.
[src:nurbs-surfaces/surface-mathematics] The apex of the cone is the origin (0, 0, 0), and is obtained for *t* = 0.
[src:nurbs-surfaces/surface-mathematics] It is an irregular point that remains irregular, whichever parametrization is chosen (otherwise, there would exist a unique tangent plane).
[src:nurbs-surfaces/surface-mathematics] Such an irregular point, where the tangent plane is undefined, is said **singular**.
[src:nurbs-surfaces/surface-mathematics] There is another kind of singular points.
[src:nurbs-surfaces/surface-mathematics] There are the **self-crossing points**, that is the points where the surface crosses itself.
[src:nurbs-surfaces/surface-mathematics] In other words, these are the points which are obtained for (at least) two different values of the parameters.
[src:nurbs-surfaces/surface-mathematics] Let *z* = *f*(*x*, *y*) be a function of two real variables, a *bivariate function*.
[src:nurbs-surfaces/surface-mathematics] Every point of this surface is regular, as the two first columns of the Jacobian matrix form the identity matrix of rank two.
[src:nurbs-surfaces/surface-mathematics] A **rational surface** is a surface that may be parametrized by rational functions of two variables.
[src:nurbs-surfaces/surface-mathematics] A rational surface is an algebraic surface, but most algebraic surfaces are not rational.
[src:nurbs-surfaces/surface-mathematics] Implicit means that the equation defines implicitly one of the variables as a function of the other variables.
[src:nurbs-surfaces/surface-mathematics] In other words, the implicit surface is the graph of a function near a point of the surface where the partial derivative in z is nonzero.
[src:nurbs-surfaces/surface-mathematics] An implicit surface has thus, locally, a parametric representation, except at the points of the surface where the three partial derivatives are zero.
[src:nurbs-surfaces/surface-mathematics] A point of the surface where at least one partial derivative of f is nonzero is called **regular**.
[src:nurbs-surfaces/surface-mathematics] At such a point $(x_{0},y_{0},z_{0})$ , the tangent plane and the direction of the normal are well defined, and may be deduced, with the implicit function theorem from the definition given above, in § Tangent plane and normal vector.
[src:nurbs-surfaces/surface-mathematics] A **singular point** of an implicit surface (in $\mathbb {R} ^{3}$ ) is a point of the surface where the implicit equation holds and the three partial derivatives of its defining function are all zero.
[src:nurbs-surfaces/surface-mathematics] Therefore, the singular points are the solutions of a system of four equations in three indeterminates.
[src:nurbs-surfaces/surface-mathematics] As most such systems have no solution, many surfaces do not have any singular point.
[src:nurbs-surfaces/surface-mathematics] A surface with no singular point is called *regular* or *non-singular*.
[src:nurbs-surfaces/surface-mathematics] The study of surfaces near their singular points and the classification of the singular points is singularity theory.
[src:nurbs-surfaces/surface-mathematics] A singular point is isolated if there is no other singular point in a neighborhood of it.
[src:nurbs-surfaces/surface-mathematics] Otherwise, the singular points may form a curve.
[src:nurbs-surfaces/surface-mathematics] This is in particular the case for self-crossing surfaces.
[src:nurbs-surfaces/surface-mathematics] where *f* is a polynomial in three indeterminates, with real coefficients.
[src:nurbs-surfaces/surface-mathematics] The concept has been extended in several directions, by defining surfaces over arbitrary fields, and by considering surfaces in spaces of arbitrary dimension or in projective spaces.
[src:nurbs-surfaces/surface-mathematics] Abstract algebraic surfaces, which are not explicitly embedded in another space, are also considered.
[src:nurbs-surfaces/surface-mathematics] Polynomials with coefficients in any field are accepted for defining an algebraic surface.
[src:nurbs-surfaces/surface-mathematics] However, the field of coefficients of a polynomial is not well defined, as, for example, a polynomial with rational coefficients may also be considered as a polynomial with real or complex coefficients.
[src:nurbs-surfaces/surface-mathematics] Therefore, the concept of *point* of the surface has been generalized in the following way.
[src:nurbs-surfaces/surface-mathematics] Given a polynomial *f*(*x*, *y*, *z*), let *k* be the smallest field containing the coefficients, and *K* be an algebraically closed extension of *k*, of infinite transcendence degree.
[src:nurbs-surfaces/surface-mathematics] If the polynomial has real coefficients, the field *K* is the complex field, and a point of the surface that belongs to $\mathbb {R} ^{3}$ (a usual point) is called a *real point*.
[src:nurbs-surfaces/surface-mathematics] A point that belongs to *k*3 is called *rational over k*, or simply a *rational point*, if *k* is the field of rational numbers.
[src:nurbs-surfaces/surface-mathematics] A **projective surface** in a projective space of dimension three is the set of points whose homogeneous coordinates are zeros of a single homogeneous polynomial in four variables.
[src:nurbs-surfaces/surface-mathematics] More generally, a projective surface is a subset of a projective space, which is a projective variety of dimension two.
[src:nurbs-surfaces/surface-mathematics] Projective surfaces are strongly related to affine surfaces (that is, ordinary algebraic surfaces).
[src:nurbs-surfaces/surface-mathematics] One passes from a projective surface to the corresponding affine surface by setting to one some coordinate or indeterminate of the defining polynomials (usually the last one).
[src:nurbs-surfaces/surface-mathematics] One cannot define the concept of an algebraic surface in a space of dimension higher than three without a general definition of an algebraic variety and of the dimension of an algebraic variety.
[src:nurbs-surfaces/surface-mathematics] In fact, an algebraic surface is an *algebraic variety of dimension two*.
[src:nurbs-surfaces/surface-mathematics] More precisely, an algebraic surface in a space of dimension n is the set of the common zeros of at least *n* – 2 polynomials, but these polynomials must satisfy further conditions that may be not immediate to verify.
[src:nurbs-surfaces/surface-mathematics] Firstly, the polynomials must not define a variety or an algebraic set of higher dimension, which is typically the case if one of the polynomials is in the ideal generated by the others.
[src:nurbs-surfaces/surface-mathematics] Generally, *n* – 2 polynomials define an algebraic set of dimension two or higher.
[src:nurbs-surfaces/surface-mathematics] If the dimension is two, the algebraic set may have several irreducible components.
[src:nurbs-surfaces/surface-mathematics] If there is only one component the *n* – 2 polynomials define a surface, which is a complete intersection.
[src:nurbs-surfaces/surface-mathematics] If there are several components, then one needs further polynomials for selecting a specific component.
[src:nurbs-surfaces/surface-mathematics] Most authors consider as an algebraic surface only algebraic varieties of dimension two, but some also consider as surfaces all algebraic sets whose irreducible components have the dimension two.
[src:nurbs-surfaces/surface-mathematics] In the case of surfaces in a space of dimension three, every surface is a complete intersection, and a surface is defined by a single polynomial, which is irreducible or not, depending on whether non-irreducible algebraic sets of dimension two are considered as surfaces or not.
[src:nurbs-surfaces/surface-mathematics] In topology, a surface is generally defined as a manifold of dimension two.
[src:nurbs-surfaces/surface-mathematics] This means that a topological surface is a topological space such that every point has a neighborhood that is homeomorphic to an open subset of a Euclidean plane.
[src:nurbs-surfaces/surface-mathematics] Every topological surface is homeomorphic to a polyhedral surface such that all facets are triangles.
[src:nurbs-surfaces/surface-mathematics] The combinatorial study of such arrangements of triangles (or, more generally, of higher-dimensional simplexes) is the starting object of algebraic topology.
[src:nurbs-surfaces/surface-mathematics] This allows the characterization of the properties of surfaces in terms of purely algebraic invariants, such as the genus and homology groups.
[src:nurbs-surfaces/surface-mathematics] The homeomorphism classes of surfaces have been completely described (see Surface (topology)).
[src:nurbs-surfaces/surface-mathematics] In mathematics, the differential geometry of surfaces deals with the differential geometry of smooth surfaces with various additional structures, most often, a Riemannian metric.
[src:nurbs-surfaces/surface-mathematics] Surfaces have been extensively studied from various perspectives: *extrinsically*, relating to their embedding in Euclidean space and *intrinsically*, reflecting their properties determined solely by the distance within the surface as measured along curves on the surface.
[src:nurbs-surfaces/surface-mathematics] One of the fundamental concepts investigated is the Gaussian curvature, first studied in depth by Carl Friedrich Gauss, who showed that curvature was an intrinsic property of a surface, independent of its isometric embedding in Euclidean space.
[src:nurbs-surfaces/surface-mathematics] Surfaces naturally arise as graphs of functions of a pair of variables, and sometimes appear in parametric form or as loci associated to space curves.
[src:nurbs-surfaces/surface-mathematics] An important role in their study has been played by Lie groups (in the spirit of the Erlangen program), namely the symmetry groups of the Euclidean plane, the sphere and the hyperbolic plane.
[src:nurbs-surfaces/surface-mathematics] These Lie groups can be used to describe surfaces of constant Gaussian curvature; they also provide an essential ingredient in the modern approach to intrinsic differential geometry through connections.
[src:nurbs-surfaces/surface-mathematics] On the other hand, extrinsic properties relying on an embedding of a surface in Euclidean space have also been extensively studied.
[src:nurbs-surfaces/surface-mathematics] A fractal landscape or fractal surface is generated using a stochastic algorithm designed to produce fractal behavior that mimics the appearance of natural terrain.
[src:nurbs-surfaces/surface-mathematics] In other words, the surface resulting from the procedure is not a deterministic, but rather a random surface that exhibits fractal behavior.
[src:nurbs-surfaces/surface-mathematics] Many natural phenomena exhibit some form of statistical self-similarity that can be modeled by fractal surfaces.
[src:nurbs-surfaces/surface-mathematics] Moreover, variations in surface texture provide important visual cues to the orientation and slopes of surfaces, and the use of almost self-similar fractal patterns can help create natural looking visual effects.
[src:nurbs-surfaces/surface-mathematics] The modeling of the Earth's rough surfaces via fractional Brownian motion was first proposed by Benoit Mandelbrot.
[src:nurbs-surfaces/surface-mathematics] Shearer, the generation of natural looking surfaces and landscapes was a major turning point in art history, where the distinction between geometric, computer generated images and natural, man made art became blurred.
[src:nurbs-surfaces/surface-mathematics] The first use of a fractal-generated landscape in a film was in 1982 for the movie *Star Trek II: The Wrath of Khan*.
[src:nurbs-surfaces/surface-mathematics] Loren Carpenter refined the techniques of Mandelbrot to create an alien landscape.
[src:nurbs-surfaces/surface-mathematics] In technical applications of 3D computer graphics (CAx) such as computer-aided design and computer-aided manufacturing, surfaces are one way of representing objects.
[src:nurbs-surfaces/surface-mathematics] The other ways are wireframe (lines and curves) and solids.
[src:nurbs-surfaces/surface-mathematics] Point clouds are also sometimes used as temporary ways to represent an object, with the goal of using the points to create one or more of the three permanent representations.
